ritings, fiction, poetry, and drama to reveal that New World gold ultimately became a problematic source of power that destabilized Spain’s sense of trust, truth, and worth. These cultural anxieties, she argues, rendered the discovery of gold paradoxically disastrous for Spanish society. Combining economic thought, social history, and literary theory in trans-Atlantic contexts, New World Gold unveils the dark side of Spain’s Golden Age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCreditxHistoryx16th centuryxSpain. 0aCreditxHistoryx17th centuryxSpain. 0aCreditzSpainxHistoryy16th century. 0aCreditzSpainxHistoryy17th century. 0aEconomicsxHistoryx16th centuryxSpain. 0aEconomicsxHistoryx17th centuryxSpain. 0aEconomicszSpainxHistoryy16th century. 0aEconomicszSpainxHistoryy17th century. 0aGoldxHistoryx16th centuryxSpain. 0aGoldxHistoryx17th centuryxSpain. 0aGoldzSpainxHistoryy16th century. 0aGoldzSpainxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226856193423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226856193.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles